menu "Wake-on-LAN"

    config WOL_BROADCAST_PORT
        int "Magic Packet UDP port"
        default 9
        range 1 65535
        help
            UDP port the Magic Packet is sent to. Port 9 (discard) is the
            WoL standard and is what all PC BIOS/NIC implementations listen
            on by default. Only change this if your target PC's NIC or
            operating system requires a non-standard port.

    config WOL_PING_FEEDBACK
        bool "Enable ping-based wake confirmation"
        default n
        help
            When enabled and a WoL command payload includes an "ip" field,
            Heimdall pings that IP after sending the magic packet and
            publishes a second MQTT response when the machine responds or
            the ping session expires. Uses the ESP-IDF non-blocking ping
            API so the MQTT client task is never blocked.
            When disabled, no ping code is compiled and the "ip" field
            in command payloads is silently ignored.

    config WOL_PING_TIMEOUT_SEC
        int "Ping timeout in seconds"
        default 120
        range 10 300
        depends on WOL_PING_FEEDBACK
        help
            How long to keep pinging after a WoL packet before declaring
            the wake attempt failed and publishing {"status":"timeout"}.
            120 seconds covers most cold-boot scenarios including POST.
            The firmware computes the ping count from this value and
            CONFIG_WOL_PING_INTERVAL_MS automatically.

    config WOL_PING_INTERVAL_MS
        int "Ping interval in milliseconds"
        default 2000
        range 500 10000
        depends on WOL_PING_FEEDBACK
        help
            How often to send an ICMP echo request during the ping session.
            2000 ms (one ping every 2 seconds) is a reasonable default for
            monitoring a booting machine without flooding the network.

    config WOL_PING_MAX_CONCURRENT
        int "Maximum concurrent ping sessions"
        default 1
        range 1 1
        depends on WOL_PING_FEEDBACK
        help
            Currently fixed at 1. If a second WoL+ping command arrives
            while a ping session is already active, the new ping is skipped
            and only the WoL packet is sent. This avoids resource leaks
            from unbounded concurrent sessions.

endmenu
